      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T16:58:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "At the cost of some complexity here, you can concatenate all consecutive matrix_3x4 stages into a single matrix stage. (Basically, as long as fInvertStyle isn\u0027t InvertLightness, you only need one matrix_3x4 and the two clamps.)",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b6eb7b21_62525763",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 388,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T16:58:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We\u0027ve stopped injecting \\t and \\n in the shader code like this. It makes it harder to read, and we now have a pretty-printer that handles formatting whenever we need to see the final shader source code.\n\nAdditionally, I think much of this would be easier to read if it things were left vectorized (rather than broken into scalars):\n\ncodeAppendf(\"vec3 color \u003d %s;\", args.fInputColor);\n...\nif (grayscale) { codeAppendf(\"color \u003d dot(color, vec3(%f %f %f));\", SK_LUM_COEFF_R, SK_LUM_COEFF_G, SK_LUM_COEFF_B); }\n...\nif (invertBrightness) { codeAppend(\"color \u003d 1 - color;\"); }\n...\nif (invertLightness) { // This stays tricky, but you can keep referring to color.r, color.g, color.b }\n...\nif (contrast) { // All of the contrast code can be executed against \u0027color\u0027, no need for per-channel }\n...\ncodeAppend(\"color \u003d clamp(color, 0, 1);\")",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ae52af2a_aa7afb3f",
        "filename": "src/effects/SkHighContrastFilter.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 403,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T16:58:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In addition to everything above, we would typically generate different shaders for the different features, rather than have the branches in the shader. So for this example:\n\nif (HighContrastInvertStyle \u003d\u003d invertStyle) {\n  codeAppend(\"color \u003d 1 - color;\");\n}\n\nFor that to work, GenKey needs to look like:\nGenKey(const GrProcessor\u0026 proc, const GrShaderCaps\u0026, GrProcessorKeyBuilder* b) {\n  const HighContrastFilterEffect \u0026hcfe \u003d proc.cast\u003cHighContrastFilterEffect\u003e();\n  b-\u003eadd32(hcfe.config().fInvertStyle);\n}\n\n... that rolls that parameter into the key we use to lookup the shader, so we cache the different variations separately. If you do this, you don\u0027t need the uniform for those parameters, and setData doesn\u0027t need to do anything either.",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "935c043c_ff486741",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 765,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "While /2 is probably going to be compiled into *0.5f by a good compiler anyway, we tend to write things like this as *0.5f or *(1/2.0f) just to make it clear that this will not be a divide.\n\nFloat divides tend to be at least 3x more expensive than a multiply or add, and that\u0027s really the best case, so we take some care to avoid them.",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d68533ad_90b32671",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 768,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "There might be some way to make these more readable at a glance, as if they were a couple ?: or a little table of cases:\n\nauto s \u003d (max \u003d\u003d min).thenElse(0.0f, \n           (l \u003e 0.5f).thenElse(d / (2.0f - max - min),\n                               d / (max + min));\n\n\nGiven that all paths will actually execute, you might want to play around with reordering this math to avoid divides.\n\n (l \u003e 0.5f).thenElse(d / (2.0f - max - min), d / (max + min));\n\n~~~~\u003e\n\n d / (l \u003e 0.5f).thenElse(2.0f - max - min, max + min);",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "dd08e77f_292c9eaa",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 768,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t mind which format you use to write integral float constants, but it\u0027s probably best we pick one of 2, 2.f or 2.0f and format the function and file consistently.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 768,
        "startChar": 60,
        "endLine": 768,
        "endChar": 63
      },
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4433412a_271cdc63",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 769,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It looks like we divide by d a few times, so it probably makes sense to multiply by (1/d), or even by d.invert() if its lower precision is good enough.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 769,
        "startChar": 41,
        "endLine": 769,
        "endChar": 44
      },
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0f57bfbc_be91775d",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 772,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is a good example of why we tend to write all these as multiplies if possible... while h /\u003d 2.0f can be compiled into a multiply, h /\u003d 6.0f will probably always be a divide.  I suspect we\u0027d rather have both be multiplies at a _very_ slight loss of precision for *(1/6.0f).",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 772,
        "startChar": 6,
        "endLine": 772,
        "endChar": 13
      },
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "821a8329_48446e27",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 785,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is entirely my opinion, but I do find it easier to read code that involves both *,/ and +,- when the * and / have no space around them and the + and - do have some space, to group them visually in the same way the math actually binds.",
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a63fe0ad_7769a190",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 790,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It\u0027s usually a good idea to get in the habit of writing float fractions with parentheses.  It doesn\u0027t matter for \u003c or +, but with *, there is an important difference between x * 1/3.0f and x * (1/3.0f).   The first is multiply-then-divide, the second just a multiply.  This is important enough that we try to write all fractions this way to keep the code looking uniform.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 790,
        "startChar": 16,
        "endLine": 790,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "bb088bcd7b22dd889806d0db4ca00bebbf7b9434",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c815b7a2_6d9dafcd",
        "filename": "src/opts/SkRasterPipeline_opts.h",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 791,
      "author": {
        "id": 5010
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-07T14:10:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It\u0027s a little weird to use 0.5f in one part of the function and (1/2.f) in another... it\u0027s probably best that we write all these constants in a consistent way within the function.  Here I imagine it\u0027d be easier to read everything as fractions.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 791,
        "startChar": 39,
        "endLine": 791,
        "endChar": 44
      },
